text: RT The text of the Constitution is clear. States select electors. Congress does not.My full statement with , , , , , and .

text: RT NEW: Statement from Texas Rep. Chip Roy () on raising a parliamentary objection to seating House members from the 6 contested states to make the point about members seating themselves but not electors:
name: Chip Roy

text: The father of our country, George Washington, famously called the Constitution ‚Äî which his wisdom helped craft and guide to fruition ‚Äî ‚Äúthe guide which I never will abandon.‚Äù We owe it the same fidelity in this case and all others.
name: Chip Roy

text: If the electors for the office of the president were not in question, neither would be the election certificates of my colleagues present here today.
name: Chip Roy

text: While the Constitution and the 12th Amendment do not make Congress the judge of the states‚Äô presidential electors, it does require us to be the arbiters of the elections to this body.
name: Chip Roy

text: I believe our body should vote on the certification of those members to ensure the integrity of the House of Representatives is guarded from all suspicion of illegitimacy.
name: Chip Roy

text: Today, I objected to the seating of my colleagues from six states: AZ, GA, MI, NV, PA, and WI.It would confound reason if the presidential results of these states were to face objection while the congressional results of the same process escaped public scrutiny.
name: Chip Roy

text: RT THIS --> "States select electors. Congress does not."The Rule of Law matters. #ElectoralCollege I am as outraged as anyone about the still-unanswered questions about the election. But the Constitution is clear:States select electors. Congress does not.There is only one path to victory for on Jan. 6: state legislatures certifying Trump electors in states at issue
name: Chip Roy

text: RT The job of Congress is to count the electors that states sent to Congress, not determine electors states should have sent. To do otherwise will destroy a foundation of our federal republic, that Congress cannot force its will on states to choose the President. #StandUpForAmerica I am as outraged as anyone about the still-unanswered questions about the election. But the Constitution is clear:States select electors. Congress does not.There is only one path to victory for on Jan. 6: state legislatures certifying Trump electors in states at issue
name: Chip Roy

text: "Absent such action, there is not a constitutional role for Congress to change the outcome of any state‚Äôs vote."
name: Chip Roy
